{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01CAcu7FpE2AHtY5SLSkecKJ","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the situation. The Elasticsearch cluster uses the file realm for authentication. The StatefulSet mounts `es-file-realm-aggregate` as a volume, but looking at the StatefulSet configuration, I don't see any volume mounts for the file realm secrets!\n\nThe Elasticsearch `elasticsearch.yml` doesn't mention file realm configuration either. And the StatefulSet only mounts:\n1. `es-config` configmap\n2. `es-certs` secret (es-http-tls)\n3. `data` PVC\n\nSo the issue is: the file realm secrets exist (`es-file-realm-aggregate` and `user-provided-file-realm`) but the Elasticsearch pods aren't using them!\nThe preconditions set up two file realm secrets—one with the ops-user as a superuser and another with the report-user as a viewer—but neither is actually mounted into the pods, and the elasticsearch configuration doesn't reference the file realm at all. To fix this, I need to mount both secrets into the StatefulSet and configure elasticsearch.yml to enable the file realm authentication provider.\n\nThe complication is that Elasticsearch's file realm can only point to a single directory, yet the users are split across two separate secrets. Since `es-file-realm-aggregate` appears to be intended as the aggregated secret, I should merge both secrets' contents into that one and then mount it as the file realm source.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2670,"cache_read_input_tokens":32529,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2670},"output_tokens":20,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"17d535c7-bc5a-47f3-bf1c-d18b808e7c60","uuid":"e33b02cf-cfb6-4564-b5de