{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_011TcSXWLm8ZFiquoMY2fRVE","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the situation clearly:\n\n1. `es-file-realm-aggregate` contains:\n   - `users`: ops-user with bcrypt hash\n   - `users_roles`: superuser:ops-user\n   - `roles.yml`: empty\n\n2. `user-provided-file-realm` contains:\n   - `users`: report-user with bcrypt hash\n   - `users_roles`: viewer:report-user\n   - `roles.yml`: empty\n\nThe ES cluster is NOT configured to use the file realm at all. There's no file realm configuration in `elasticsearch.yml`, and neither secret is mounted into the pods.\nTo get `report-user` working without disrupting `ops-user`, I need to merge both user sets into `es-file-realm-aggregate`, mount it into the ES pods, and configure the file realm in `elasticsearch.yml`. Since the StatefulSet is already running with 3 pods, updating it will trigger a rolling restart, so the files need to be accessible at the correct paths during that process. and mount both files to the config directory, which will trigger a rolling restart of the pods. But looking back at the precondition, it seems like `ops-user` and `report-user` were already created in separate secrets, so I'm not actually breaking any existing users—the only currently authenticated user is `elastic`, the built-in superuser. The secret name with \"aggregate\" in it suggests it's meant to combine all file realm users, but neither secret is actually mounted as a volume in the StatefulSet—only the config, certs, and data volumes are present. So the real issue is that the file realm secrets aren't being used at all, which is why neither ops-user nor report-user can authenticate.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":468,"cache_read_input_tokens":36235,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input